04078nam a22006255i 9780292797093DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927970937 a10.7560/7063302doi  a(DE-B1597)588669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a371.82968/0732221 aPortales, Rita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuality Education for Latinos and Latinas :bPrint and Oral Skills for All Students, K–College /cMarco Portales, Rita Portales. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Education and Latino and Latina Students Today -- tPart II. How to Repair an Education System -- tPart III. A Print and Oral Approach -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs educators and legislators across the country debate how to improve public schools, the most vital factor often disappears from the equation—the relationship between the teacher and the student. According to veteran educators Rita and Marco Portales, this relationship is the central issue in the education of students, especially Latino/a students who often face serious barriers to school success because of the legacy of racism, insufficient English-language skills, and cultural differences with the educational establishment. To break down these barriers and help Latino/a students acquire a quality education, the Portaleses focus attention on the teacher-student relationship and offer a proven method that teachers can use to strengthen the print and oral skills of their students. They begin by analyzing the reasons why schools too often fail to educate Latino/a students, using eloquent comments from young Latinos/as and their parents to confirm how important the teacher-student relationship is to the student's success. Then they show how all educational stakeholders—teachers, administrators, state education agencies, legislators, and parents—can work together to facilitate the teacher-student relationship and improve student education. By demonstrating how teachers can improve students' reading, critical thinking, writing, and oral communication skills across the curriculum, they argue that learning can be made more relevant for students, keeping their interest levels high while preparing them for academically competitive colleges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLatin American studentszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aLatin AmericansxEducationzUnited States. 0aMulticultural educationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aPortales, Marco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797093/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK